07534nam a22009015i 9781800105393DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818001053937 a10.1515/97818001053932doi  a(DE-B1597)675897  a(OCoLC)1313885698  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a780.9440903422300aAmerica in the French Imaginary, 1789-1914 :bMusic, Revolution and Race /ced. by César A. Leal, Diana R. Hallman. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (410 p.) :b40 b/w, 18 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMusic in Society and Culture ;v1000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Music Examples -- tList of Abbreviations -- tEditorial Notes -- tList of Contributors -- tAcknowledgements -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. American liberté, sauvagerie and esclavage -- t1 Between Amérique and Colonial France: Revolutionary Tales of liberté and esclavage -- t2 Justamant’s Le Bossu and Depictions of Indigenous Americans in Nineteenth-Century French Ballet -- t3 Louisiana Imagined: Gender, Race and Slavery in Le Planteur (1839) -- tPart II. Myths of America and Intersecting Identities -- t4 ‘Brise du Sud’: American Identity and War in the Popular Sheet Music of Francophone New Orleans -- t5 ‘The Most Seductive Creole Indolence’: Louis Moreau Gottschalk in the French Press -- t6 Symphonies from the New World: The Myths and Realities of American Orchestral Music in France -- tPart III. Soundscapes and Sonic Fantasies -- t7 Historical Acoustemology in the French Romantic Travelogue: Chateaubriand’s Sonic Imagining of the New World -- t8 La Liberté éclairant le monde: Transatlantic Soundscapes for the Statue of Liberty -- tPart IV. America, Commodification and Race at the fin de siècle -- t9 Buffalo Bill and the Sound of America during the 1889 World’s Fair -- t10 Cakewalking in Paris: New Representations and Contexts of African American Culture -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJust as America was observed in French literary and political commentary, we find representations of America in French music, dance, and theatre which serve as the focus of this volume. Following the American Revolution, French authors often viewed the United States as a laboratory for the forging of new practices of liberté and égalité, in affinity with France's own Revolutionary ideals but in competition with lingering anti-American depictions of an inferior, untamed New World. The volume examines French imagining of America through musical/theatrical portrayals of the American Revolution and Republic, soundscapes of the Statue of Liberty, homages to Washington, Franklin and Lafayette and negotiations of Francophone identity in New Orleans. The subject of race features prominently in paradoxical depictions of slavery, freedom, and revolution in the United States and French Caribbean colonies of 'Amérique' and in varied interpretations of American music and gendered identity. Essays consider French constructions of the Indigenous American and Black American 'exotic' that intersect with tropes of noble, pastoral savagery, menacing barbarism and the 'civilising' potency of French culture. Such French constructions reveal both a revulsion of racial alterity and an attraction to the expressive, even subversive, freedom of Americanness. Investigations of French conceptions of America extend to critiques of American orchestral music, Gottschalk's Louisianan-Caribbean Creole works, Buffalo Bill's spectacles and the cakewalk in Paris. With scholarly contributions on music, dance, theatre and opera, the volume will be essential reading for students and scholars of these disciplines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.